<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911121-0164</DOCNO><DOCID>911121-0164.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Japanese Computer Sales Fall</HL><DATE>11/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><RE>FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)</RE><LP>   TOKYO -- Sales of Japanese personal computers andperipheral equipment for the six months ended Sept. 30slipped an average 3.6% from the year-earlier period to 598.3billion yen ($4.61 billion), the Electronic IndustriesAssociation of Japan reported.   The year-on-year sales decline marks the first drop everrecorded for a fiscal half, association officials said.</LP><TEXT>   In light of the world-wide market slump for computers,Japanese manufacturers would be lucky to see sales grow even8% for the entire fiscal year, much less than the 21%originally forecast, one official said. The fiscal year endsMarch 31, 1992.   Domestic sales of personal computers and related equipmentgrew 3.7% in the April-September period to 466.9 billion yen,but overseas sales dropped 23% to 131.4 billion yen. Marketconditions in the U.S. were particularly bad, the officialssaid.   Combined domestic and overseas sales of 32-bit personalcomputers grew 81% to 257.4 billion yen, with 16-bit modelsfalling 60% to 76.6 billion yen and 8-bit units plunging 73%to 900 million yen.   Sales of peripherals, including printers, displays anddisk-drive equipment, fell 7% to 263.4 billion yen.</TEXT></DOC>